When Mr. Keats errs in his poetry, it is from the ill management of a good thing, — exuberance of ideas. Once or twice, he does so in a taste positively bad, like Marino or Cowley, as in a line in his Ode to Psyche
At tender eye-dawn of aurorean love;
but it is once or twice only, in his present volume. Nor has erred much in it in a nobler way. What we allude to is one or two passages in which he over-informsoverinforms the occasion or the speaker; as where the brothers, for instance, whom he describes as a couple of mere "money-bags," are gifted with the power of uttering the following exquisite metaphor: —
